+Key Relationships
+The schema is heavily interconnected. The most important relationships:
+	•	messages → threads (every message belongs to a thread)
+	•	threads → team_members (every team thread is with one person)
+	•	tasks → team_members (owner) and tasks → messages (origin) (tasks know who owns them and what conversation birthed them)
+	•	tasks → projects (many-to-one — projects contain tasks as milestones)
+	•	followups → tasks (many-to-one — multiple nudges per task)
+	•	escalations → tasks + followups (an escalation traces back to the chase that triggered it)
+	•	emails → email_accounts (every email belongs to one of three accounts)
+	•	email_drafts → emails (reply_to) (drafts can reply to a specific email or start a new thread)
+	•	insights → analysis_runs (every insight came from a specific Opus run)
+	•	sops ← insights (approved insights become SOPs)
+	•	agent_actions_log (loosely references everything via entity_type + entity_id, on purpose — log is the cross-cutting record)
+Design Notes
+Why UUIDs everywhere
+UUID primary keys allow the agent to generate IDs client-side before insert, which simplifies the message-creation flow (PWA generates the ID, sends to server, server stores). Also makes it safe to merge databases later if we ever spin up a separate environment.
+Why JSONB instead of joined tables for some fields
+Fields like responsibilities, working_hours, depends_on, evidence, and milestones are read together with the parent row 100% of the time and rarely queried independently. JSONB gives us schema flexibility without join cost. We add indexed columns when we need to query a JSONB key — but most of these never need that.
+Why soft deletes
+Anything Selmen has touched should not disappear. If a task is cancelled six months later, we want to be able to look back and see what happened. Soft delete (deleted_at) means we filter at query time but never lose history.
+Why agent_actions_log is loosely-coupled
+The log uses (entity_type, entity_id) instead of a hard FK so that we can log actions on entities that may later be hard-deleted, on entities that span multiple tables (e.g. a 'briefing' isn't a single row), or on system-level actions with no entity at all. The tradeoff is no referential integrity on this column — that's fine because the log is append-only history, not an authoritative pointer.
+Migration strategy
+Drizzle generates migrations from the schema TypeScript file. Every change to the schema produces a new versioned migration. Migrations are applied to staging first, validated, then applied to production. Never edit production schema by hand. The Build Environment Setup Guide (Document 03) covers the migration workflow in detail.
+This schema is the foundation. Once it's in place, every phase of the build adds capabilities that read from and write to these tables. Keep it stable — schema changes after Phase 2 will be expensive to coordinate.
