+5. The Shadow Team
+Staging needs fake versions of every real team member, so the agent can dispatch tasks, send follow-ups, and trigger escalations end-to-end without any real team member ever receiving a test message.
+5.1 Setup
+Create a separate set of contacts for staging. Three options for the receiving end:
+	•	Use Google Voice numbers (free, multiple numbers per Google account, easy to set up)
+	•	Use a few personal SIM cards on cheap phones if you have them lying around
+	•	Use your own number with the contact name prefixed TEST- so messages thread separately
+The simplest and most realistic: get 4-5 Google Voice numbers, label them TEST-Oscar, TEST-Nick, TEST-Brandon, TEST-Orlando, TEST-Karina. Forward those to your phone. The agent in staging routes to those numbers.
+5.2 Shadow team in the database
+Seed the staging database's team_members table with the same names and roles as production, but with the test phone numbers and emails. Same structure, different recipients. The code is identical — only the data differs.
+5.3 Test email account
+For email testing in staging, set up a Gmail account like cos-test@takeoversrentals.com (or use a Gmail alias). Connect that account via OAuth in staging. Real production accounts (sel@, selmen@yourmusicmanager.com, soselman@gmail.com) are only ever connected to production.
+This setup adds about a day to project kickoff. It saves you from one bad deploy that costs you team trust forever. The math is unambiguous.
