+7. Database Migrations
+Drizzle ORM handles schema management. Every schema change becomes a versioned migration file checked into git.
+7.1 Workflow
+	•	Edit packages/db/schema.ts to add/change a table or column
+	•	Generate migration: pnpm drizzle-kit generate
+	•	Review the generated SQL in packages/db/migrations/
+	•	Commit both the schema change AND the migration file in the same commit
+	•	Apply to local: pnpm drizzle-kit migrate
+	•	Push branch, merge to staging — staging auto-runs migrations on deploy
+	•	Verify staging works as expected with new schema
+	•	Merge staging to main — production auto-runs migrations
+7.2 Migration safety rules
+NEVER edit a production database schema by hand. NEVER. Every schema change is a migration file. This is non-negotiable because it's the only way to keep all three environments synchronized.
+	•	Migrations are forward-only in production. No automatic rollback.
+	•	If a migration breaks production, write a new forward migration that fixes it.
+	•	For destructive changes (dropping columns, removing tables), do them in two phases: first stop writing to the column in code (deploy), then drop the column in a later migration after confirming no code references it.
+	•	Backup production before any migration that touches existing data.
+7.3 Initial migration
+Phase 1 will produce the initial migration that creates all 17 tables and 21 enums. Run it once against each environment's empty database. From that point forward, every schema evolution is incremental.
+
+8. Backups
+8.1 What needs backing up
+	•	Postgres production database — everything. This is Selmen's second brain.
+	•	S3 storage bucket — voice memos, email attachments. Less critical but valuable.
+	•	n8n workflow exports — checked into the /n8n folder of the repo. Version controlled with code.
+	•	Replit secrets — manually exported and stored in 1Password (or similar) every quarter.
+8.2 Postgres backup schedule
+	•	Daily automated dump → S3 (or Replit's backup service) → retained 30 days rolling
+	•	Weekly snapshot → retained 90 days
+	•	Monthly snapshot → retained 12 months
+8.3 Backup script
+A simple cron-driven script in /scripts handles it. Replit can run this on a schedule:
+#!/bin/bash
+# scripts/backup-db.sh
+
+TIMESTAMP=$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)
+BACKUP_FILE="cos-prod-${TIMESTAMP}.sql.gz"
+
+pg_dump $DATABASE_URL | gzip > /tmp/$BACKUP_FILE
+
+aws s3 cp /tmp/$BACKUP_FILE s3://takeovers-cos-backups/daily/
+rm /tmp/$BACKUP_FILE
+
+# Cleanup: delete backups older than 30 days from daily/
+aws s3 ls s3://takeovers-cos-backups/daily/ \
+  | awk '{print $4}' | head -n -30 \
+  | xargs -I{} aws s3 rm s3://takeovers-cos-backups/daily/{}
+8.4 Recovery procedure
+Document the recovery procedure now, while the system is healthy. You don't want to be reading documentation for the first time during a real outage.
+	•	Identify which backup to restore from (check timestamp)
+	•	Download backup: aws s3 cp s3://takeovers-cos-backups/daily/[file] .
+	•	Decompress: gunzip [file]
+	•	Spin up a fresh Postgres instance (do NOT restore over production directly)
+	•	Restore: psql $NEW_DB_URL < [file]
+	•	Verify the restored data is intact (recent tasks, threads, messages)
+	•	Update DATABASE_URL in Replit secrets to point at the restored DB
+	•	Redeploy. Monitor.
+8.5 Backup restore drill
+Once a quarter, do a fire-drill: restore a recent backup to a temporary Postgres instance and verify the system runs against it. This catches backup corruption or schema drift before a real outage.
+
+9. Replit Deployment Configuration
+9.1 Two Replit deployments off one repo
+Replit supports multiple deployments from the same repository. Configure two:
+	•	takeovers-cos-staging → tracks the staging branch → deploys to staging.cos.takeoversrentals.com
+	•	takeovers-cos-prod → tracks the main branch → deploys to cos.takeoversrentals.com
+9.2 Auto-deploy hooks
+Each Replit deployment is connected via GitHub webhook. On push to its tracked branch, Replit pulls, builds, runs migrations, and restarts the service. Build command and start command are defined in the repo's package.json scripts.
+9.3 Build and start scripts
+// package.json (root)
+{
+  "scripts": {
+    "build": "pnpm -r build",
+    "build:web": "pnpm --filter web build",
+    "build:api": "pnpm --filter api build",
+    "db:migrate": "pnpm --filter db migrate",
+    "start": "pnpm db:migrate && pnpm --filter api start",
+    "dev": "pnpm -r --parallel dev"
+  }
+}
+9.4 Health check endpoint
+The API exposes /health which Replit polls. Returns 200 if Postgres, Redis, and core services are reachable; 500 otherwise. Replit auto-restarts if /health fails repeatedly.
+// apps/api/src/routes/health.ts
+router.get('/health', async (req, res) => {
+  try {
+    await db.execute('SELECT 1');
+    await redis.ping();
+    res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date() });
+  } catch (e) {
+    res.status(500).json({ status: 'error', error: e.message });
+  }
+});
+9.5 Custom domain setup
+	•	Buy or use existing takeoversrentals.com domain
+	•	In Replit deployment settings, add custom domain cos.takeoversrentals.com (production)
+	•	Replit shows you a CNAME record to add to your DNS
+	•	Add the CNAME at your domain registrar (e.g. GoDaddy, Cloudflare)
+	•	Wait 10-30 minutes for propagation
+	•	Repeat for staging.cos.takeoversrentals.com pointing at the staging deployment
+	•	Replit auto-provisions SSL certificates via Let's Encrypt
