+TAKEOVERS CHIEF OF STAFF
+Phase 3
+Email Handling
+Document 06 of 13
+Estimated build time: 2 weeks
+Outcome: Three Gmail accounts read, triaged, drafted, and sent — with the personal account on tight rails.
+
+Phase Goal
+Phase 3 brings the agent's email capability online across all three Gmail accounts: sel@takeoversrentals.com (main business), selmen@yourmusicmanager.com (account hub), and soselman@gmail.com (personal). Each account has a different role and the agent treats them differently — full two-tier authority on the business account, mostly triage on the account hub, and conservative draft-only behavior on the personal account.
+This is the riskiest phase in the build. Sending email as Selmen means a bad draft can damage a vendor relationship, a partner relationship, or a legal one. Section 9 (Risks) and the per-account authority model are the most important parts of this document. Read them twice.
+What you can do at the end of Phase 3:
+	•	Inbox tab shows unified view across all three accounts with sub-tabs per account
+	•	Newsletters, receipts, and obvious automation are auto-archived
+	•	Internal team email replies are auto-handled when confidence is high
+	•	External emails surface as drafts in the Approvals tab
+	•	Forward / archive / label actions are taken autonomously where authority allows
+	•	Per-account kill switches in PWA settings — toggle each account's authority independently
+What is explicitly NOT in this phase:
+	•	No multi-step email workflows (e.g. "draft a follow-up if no reply in 3 days" — that's Phase 4 chase logic applied to email)
+	•	No email-driven task creation from external senders (Phase 6 surfaces this as a learning suggestion)
+	•	No email signature management (set once during setup)
+
+1. The Three Gmail Accounts — Behavior Per Account
+1.1 sel@takeoversrentals.com — Main Business
+Role: Most team and partner correspondence. The default email account.
+This account has full two-tier authority. The agent reads everything, classifies, and acts based on the rules below.
+Auto-handle (Tier A) rules for this account
+	•	Internal team replies that match a clear acknowledgment pattern ("got it", "thanks", "approved", "will do")
+	•	Forwarding misrouted internal emails (e.g. someone CC'd by mistake)
+	•	Archiving newsletters, receipts, ticketing notifications, automated calendar invites
+	•	Acknowledging receipt of something with a 1-2 sentence reply when the original sender is internal AND the agent's confidence in the reply is >= 0.85
+Draft-only (Tier B) rules for this account
+	•	Anything to a partner (Brandon Lherisson, Richard Hernandez)
+	•	Anything to legal counsel
+	•	Anything to Karina (realtor) or external brokers
+	•	Anything involving money, contracts, payment terms, or commitments
+	•	Replies longer than ~3 sentences
+	•	Anything to a contact the agent hasn't communicated with before
+	•	Anything where the agent's confidence is below 0.85
+1.2 selmen@yourmusicmanager.com — Account Hub
+Role: The administrative account where Google Ads, vendor receipts, billing, and platform notifications live. High-volume, low-reply.
+This account is treated as a triage stream. Almost nothing gets a reply, but a lot needs to be filed correctly or surfaced if action is required.
+Auto-handle (Tier A) rules for this account
+	•	Aggressive auto-archive — newsletters, marketing, receipts under $50, automated reports, social media notifications
+	•	Auto-label by sender or topic (Google Ads, AWS, Twilio, etc.)
+	•	Forward billing alerts to sel@takeoversrentals.com if they need action
+Surface-to-Selmen rules
+	•	Account suspensions, policy violations, payment failures, or security alerts
+	•	Receipts over $500 (in case manual review is needed)
+	•	Anything from Google Ads about disapproved ads or account warnings
+	•	Anything from a payment processor about chargebacks or disputes
+Draft-only (Tier B) rules
+Almost no replies get drafted from this account. If a vendor asks a question requiring a response, the agent forwards it to sel@takeoversrentals.com instead of drafting from yourmusicmanager.com.
+1.3 soselman@gmail.com — Personal
+Role: Personal email — sensitive, outside business scope.
+This account operates on the tightest rails of all three. The agent should NEVER send anything from this account autonomously, even if rules would otherwise permit it. This is non-negotiable. Personal email is too high-stakes.
+Auto-handle (Tier A) rules — narrow
+	•	Auto-archive newsletters and obvious marketing (only when sender is on a known auto-archive list)
+	•	Auto-archive receipts from personal services (Apple, Amazon receipts, Uber, etc.)
+	•	Auto-archive social network notifications
+	•	That's it. Nothing else.
+Draft-only (Tier B) — default for everything else
+	•	Any email from a person (not automated) gets surfaced for Selmen's eyes
+	•	Drafts are NEVER auto-sent from this account, regardless of confidence score
+	•	If Selmen explicitly tells the agent "reply to this from my personal account," the agent drafts it for review — never sends without explicit approval
+Persistent setting
+The feature flag auto_email_reply_personal is locked to OFF. Even if Selmen toggles it ON via the PWA, a server-side check rejects the change with the message: "This flag is permanently disabled for the personal account. Contact Selmen if this needs to change."
+The personal account is the one I'd be most worried about. Sending an inappropriate or wrong reply from a personal email is a different category of risk than sending the same from a business email. Lock it down hard and only loosen later if there's a clear reason — there usually isn't.
+
+2. Gmail API Integration
+2.1 OAuth setup
+	•	One Google Cloud project (Takeovers CoS)
+	•	OAuth consent screen configured as 'Internal' or 'External Testing' — not public
+	•	Three OAuth client IDs (one per environment): localhost dev, staging, production
+	•	Selmen authorizes each Gmail account once during setup, by clicking through the OAuth flow
+	•	Refresh tokens stored in email_accounts.oauth_refresh_token, encrypted at rest with ENCRYPTION_KEY
+2.2 OAuth scopes
+Use the minimum scopes needed. Gmail API is sensitive — Google reviews scope requests if the OAuth screen is set to public. Internal/Testing mode avoids review but limits to specific email addresses.
+// Required scopes for Phase 3:
+https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly      // Read inbox
+https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.modify        // Archive, label
+https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.compose       // Create drafts
+https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.send          // Send (already from Phase 2)
+https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.labels        // Manage labels
+
+// NOT used:
+// gmail.metadata     // Too restrictive — we need bodies
+// gmail.settings.*   // We don't change account settings
+2.3 Sync strategy
+The agent does NOT poll Gmail every minute — that hits API rate limits fast. Instead, use Gmail's history-based sync.
+Initial sync (one-time per account)
+	•	Fetch the user's most recent historyId via users.getProfile
+	•	Use users.messages.list to fetch the last 7 days of messages
+	•	For each message, fetch metadata + classify + decide action
+	•	Store historyId in email_accounts.last_history_id
+Incremental sync (every 5 minutes via cron)
+	•	Call users.history.list since last_history_id
+	•	For each new message in the response, fetch full message
+	•	Run classification pipeline
+	•	Update last_history_id
+Real-time push notifications (recommended for production)
+Gmail supports push notifications via Google Cloud Pub/Sub. Setup adds complexity but means inbound emails are processed within seconds instead of waiting for the 5-minute cron.
+	•	Set up a Pub/Sub topic in Google Cloud
+	•	Call users.watch on each Gmail account, pointing at the topic
+	•	Set up a Cloud Run or Pub/Sub push endpoint that POSTs to /api/webhooks/gmail-push
+	•	Watch must be renewed every 7 days — set up a cron to do that automatically
+Phase 3 can ship with the 5-minute cron sync. Push notifications are an optimization. Add them later if Selmen finds the 5-minute lag annoying — usually not a deal-breaker for inbox triage.
+
+3. Email Classification Pipeline
+Every inbound email runs through this pipeline immediately on receipt.
+3.1 Pipeline stages
+	•	Fetch full message (subject, body, headers, attachments)
+	•	Lightweight rule-based pre-classification — auto-archive obvious patterns without calling Claude
+	•	If not pre-classified: send to Claude for classification
+	•	Apply action based on classification + account tier rules
+	•	Log to agent_actions_log
+3.2 Lightweight pre-classification rules
+These run in the API code without Claude — saving cost and latency on obvious cases.
+	•	Sender domain matches known newsletter list (substack.com, mailchimp domains, etc.) → auto-archive
+	•	Subject contains "Receipt", "Invoice #", "Order #" → tag as receipt, archive if from known auto-archive senders
+	•	List-Unsubscribe header present + sender not in team_members → likely marketing, classify as newsletter
+	•	Sender is a known automated address (no-reply@*, notifications@*) → tag automated, evaluate further
+3.3 Claude classification prompt
+SYSTEM:
+Classify an email for Selmen's Chief of Staff agent.
+
+Account: {account.account_email}
+Account role: {account.account_role}
+
+Email:
+  From: {email.from}
+  To: {email.to}
+  Subject: {email.subject}
+  Body (first 2000 chars): {email.body[:2000]}
+
+Sender context (if known):
+  Team member: {team_member or null}
+  Partner: {is_partner}
+  External: {is_external}
+  Past communication: {prior_email_count} emails over {prior_email_days} days
+
+Return JSON:
+{
+  "classification": "newsletter" | "receipt" | "team" | "partner" | "external" | "personal" | "spam" | "automated" | "action_required",
+  "importance_score": 0-100,
+  "requires_response": boolean,
+  "recommended_action": "archive" | "flag" | "forward" | "draft_reply" | "auto_reply" | "no_action",
+  "draft_reply_text": null | "if recommended_action is auto_reply or draft_reply",
+  "draft_reply_confidence": 0-1,
+  "reasoning": "why you chose this",
+  "contains_task_for_selmen": boolean,
+  "task_summary": null | "if contains_task_for_selmen"
+}
+3.4 Action routing
+Based on the classification + the account's tier rules, the agent takes one of these actions:
+Action
+When
+Logged as
+auto_archive
+Newsletter, receipt under threshold, automated notification
+emails.agent_action = 'archived'
+auto_reply
+Confidence >= 0.85, internal team, simple ack pattern
