+Phase Goal
+Phase 4 closes the third and most operationally important loop: Chase. The agent now monitors every dispatched task, sends nudges at appropriate intervals, and escalates to Selmen when team members go silent past the threshold.
+This is the loop that prevents Fareharbor-style fires. Selmen's pain isn't generating tasks or sending them — it's the gap between dispatch and follow-up. By the end of Phase 4, that gap is closed automatically.
+Phase 4 also extends chase logic to email — drafts that sit unactioned, conversations awaiting reply, important emails Selmen flagged but didn't action. The agent now actively manages a queue of "things still in motion."
+What you can do at the end of Phase 4:
+	•	Every dispatched task has automatic nudges scheduled at appropriate intervals
+	•	Team members get soft → firm → escalate progression based on silence duration
+	•	Escalations push to Selmen via SMS with recommended actions
+	•	Email drafts sitting in Approvals nudge Selmen if unactioned for too long
+	•	Important flagged emails follow the same chase pattern
+	•	Today tab shows a dedicated 'Awaiting' section for in-flight items
+What is explicitly NOT in this phase:
+	•	No project-level chase logic (Phase 5 — milestone-aware chase)
+	•	No learning of personalized chase intervals (Phase 6)
+	•	No automatic re-dispatch to a backup person (manual decision for now)
+
+1. The Follow-up Scheduler
+The follow-up scheduler is a background job that runs every 5 minutes, finds all followups rows where scheduled_for <= NOW() AND status = 'pending', and processes them.
+1.1 Default cadence per priority
+Priority
+Nudge 1 (soft)
+Nudge 2 (firm)
+Nudge 3 (escalate)
+Behavior
+urgent
++4h
++8h
++12h (escalates)
+Tight cadence; escalation triggers SMS to Selmen
+high
++12h
++24h
++36h
+Day-and-a-half escalation window
+normal
++24h
++48h
++72h
+Standard 3-day window — most tasks fall here
+low
++72h
++5 days
++7 days
+Patient cadence; low-priority items don't burn attention
+1.2 Cadence is dispatched-time-relative
+Nudges are scheduled relative to dispatched_at, not to created_at. The clock starts when the task left the agent's outbound, not when Selmen captured it.
+1.3 Cadence honors working hours
+If a nudge would fire outside the team member's working_hours, it shifts to the next working hour. Example: Test-Orlando works 8 AM - 8 PM. A nudge scheduled for 11 PM Tuesday shifts to 8 AM Wednesday. This avoids waking people up but keeps Selmen's escalation window honest — the silence duration is still measured against the original schedule.
+1.4 Cadence pauses when responses come in
+Any inbound message from a team member on a task's thread satisfies pending nudges automatically:
+	•	Reply categorized as 'acknowledgment' or 'working_on_it' → satisfies nudge 1, advances to nudge 2 with re-scheduled clock
+	•	Reply categorized as 'completed' → cancels all remaining nudges, marks task complete
+	•	Reply categorized as 'blocked' → cancels nudges, creates an escalation row immediately (Selmen needs to see blockers)
+	•	Reply with question → satisfies current nudge, awaits next agent action (auto-reply if Tier A, draft if Tier B)
+1.5 The clock resets on agent re-engagement
+If Selmen replies on the thread (or if the agent sends a new message that's not a nudge), the chase clock resets. This prevents the agent from firing a nudge 3 hours after Selmen and the team member just finished a back-and-forth.
+
+2. Nudge Message Generation
+2.1 Nudge level 1 — soft
+Tone: friendly, no pressure. Acknowledges the person is busy. Often uses the team member's communication style preference.
+Detailed style nudge (for Nick, Josh, Oscar)
+Hey Nick, just circling back on the tracking pixel update I
+sent over yesterday. No rush — just wanted to make sure it
+didn't get buried. Let me know if anything's blocking it.
+
+[link to original task]
+Terse style nudge (for Orlando, Joan, others)
+Hey Orlando — circling back on the trail check. Status?
+2.2 Nudge level 2 — firm
+Tone: still friendly but explicit about the timeline. Mentions the deadline if there is one. Asks for an ETA.
+Detailed firm nudge
+Hey Nick — wanted to follow up again on the tracking pixel.
+Original ask was 48 hours ago. Are we good to ship by
+Friday or do you need more time / something unblocked?
+Terse firm nudge
+Orlando — still need a status on the trail check. ETA?
+2.3 Nudge level 3 — escalation (different mechanic)
+Level 3 is NOT another message to the team member. It's an escalation to Selmen. The agent does NOT keep nudging the team member into the void — the escalation handoff to Selmen is the next correct action.
+	•	Creates an escalations row
+	•	Surfaces in Today tab under 'Needs your attention'
+	•	Sends SMS push to Selmen
+	•	Pauses further nudges on this task — the clock stops because the ball is now in Selmen's court
+This is intentional design. Continuing to nudge a team member who isn't responding wastes goodwill and trains them to ignore the agent. After two nudges, escalation is the operationally correct move — Selmen makes a phone call, takes a different action, or accepts the silence.
+2.4 Nudge prompt for Claude
+SYSTEM:
+Generate a follow-up message from Selmen's Chief of Staff agent
+to a team member.
+
+Original task: "{task.description}"
+Original message sent: "{original_message.body}"
+Original message sent at: {original_message.created_at}
+Time since dispatch: {hours_since_dispatch} hours
+Nudge level: {nudge_level} (1 = soft, 2 = firm)
+
+Owner: {owner.full_name}
+Communication style: {owner.communication_style}
+Recent messages from owner: {recent_replies}
+
+Draft the nudge in Selmen's voice, in the owner's style.
+If level 1: friendly, low pressure, acknowledge they may be busy.
+If level 2: still friendly but explicit about timeline + ask for ETA.
+Never sound passive-aggressive.
+Never use guilt-trip language.
+
+Return JSON:
+{
+  "channel": "sms" | "email" (match original task channel),
+  "subject": null | "if email",
+  "body": "the nudge",
+  "reasoning": "why this approach"
+}
