+TAKEOVERS CHIEF OF STAFF
+Phase 5
+Projects
+Document 08 of 13
+Estimated build time: 2 weeks
+Outcome: Multi-step initiatives are tracked structurally — milestones, owners, dependencies, risks.
+
+Phase Goal
+Phase 4 prevents Fareharbor-style fires at the task level — silence on a single task escalates. Phase 5 prevents them at the project level — multi-step initiatives get planned, tracked structurally, and watched for systemic risk before any single task is even due.
+A project is a coherent multi-step effort with milestones, owners, dependencies, and a target completion. The Fareharbor migration would have been a project. The Dallas grand opening is a project. A new SOP rollout is a project. The agent's job is to detect when something is a project, propose the structure, and then track it as one — so that even if individual tasks haven't yet missed deadlines, the agent can spot "this initiative is at risk" and surface it.
+This is also where the agent starts to feel like a real Chief of Staff rather than just a task router. Project-level thinking is a different mode of operation.
+What you can do at the end of Phase 5:
+	•	Brain-dump a multi-step initiative — agent detects it as a project and proposes structure
+	•	Approve, edit, or reject the proposed structure
+	•	View all active projects in the Projects tab with progress, owners, risk status
+	•	Drill into a project to see milestones, dependencies, recent activity, agent observations
+	•	Receive proactive risk alerts when a project drifts off-track
+	•	Have the daily brief flag projects at risk before any task explicitly fails
+What is explicitly NOT in this phase:
+	•	No Gantt charts or visual timeline UI (consider in v2)
+	•	No external sharing of project views with partners (security/scope concern)
+	•	No automated re-planning when a milestone slips (agent surfaces the slip; replan is human decision)
+	•	No project templates yet (Phase 6 learning generates these from observed patterns)
+
+1. What Counts as a Project
+Not every task should become a project. The overhead of project structure is only worth it for genuinely multi-step efforts.
+Heuristics for project detection
+During capture, Claude evaluates whether the input describes a project. Triggers:
+	•	Three or more distinct sub-asks in one brain-dump
+	•	Mention of multiple team members needing to coordinate
+	•	A timeline longer than 2 weeks
+	•	Words like "migration", "launch", "rollout", "opening", "campaign", "transition"
+	•	Reference to dependencies ("after X, then Y", "before we can launch", "once Y is done")
+	•	Operational scope ("new location", "new system", "end-to-end")
+What stays a single task
+	•	Single ask to a single person
+	•	Routine operational work
+	•	Items completable in under a few days
+	•	Items without dependencies
+Edge cases
+If detection is ambiguous, default to single task. Selmen can promote a task to a project later from the Today tab. Better to under-promote than to spam project structure on routine work.
+In the first month of Phase 5 production, expect 3-5 active projects at any time, not 30. The Projects tab is meant to feel curated, not noisy. If it gets noisy, tune detection to be more conservative.
+
+2. Project Detection & Proposal Flow
+2.1 During capture
+	•	Selmen brain-dumps something that looks project-shaped
+	•	Claude's capture parser returns type='project' with proposed structure
+	•	Agent surfaces the proposal in the Talk tab: "This sounds like a project. Want me to plan it out?"
+	•	Selmen can: Yes (proceed to plan), No (treat as task), or Edit before approving
+2.2 Project planning prompt
+When Selmen says yes, the agent runs a planning prompt against Claude Opus (this is one of the few places where Opus is worth the cost):
+SYSTEM:
+You are planning a project for Selmen Hassen, CEO of Takeovers Rentals.
+
+Selmen brain-dumped: "{capture_text}"
+
+Available team members and their responsibilities:
+{team_members_with_responsibilities_json}
+
+Your job: propose a structured project plan with milestones,
+suggested owners, dependencies, and a target completion date.
+
+Each milestone should be:
+  - Clear and concrete (something with a definite 'done' state)
+  - Owned by exactly one team member (the one most aligned to the work)
+  - Sequenced via dependencies where order matters
+  - Sized for completion within ~5 days each
+
+Identify risks proactively. What could go wrong? What's outside
+the team's control? Who needs to coordinate?
+
+Return JSON:
+{
+  "project": {
+    "name": "short name, max 100 chars",
+    "description": "what this project is and why it matters",
+    "target_completion": "ISO date",
+    "lead": "team_member name (the one most accountable)",
+    "risk_level": "low" | "normal" | "elevated" | "critical",
+    "risk_notes": "why risk is what it is"
+  },
+  "milestones": [
+    {
+      "sequence": 1,
+      "title": "short title",
+      "description": "what's done when this is done",
+      "proposed_owner": "team_member name",
+      "proposed_due": "ISO date",
+      "depends_on": [list of milestone sequence numbers],
+      "reasoning": "why this owner, why this date"
+    },
+    ...
+  ],
+  "observations": [
+    "agent observations about risk, coordination, or scope"
+  ]
+}
+2.3 Proposal review UI
+After Claude returns the plan, the PWA shows a project preview screen:
+	•	Project name, description, target date, lead — editable inline
+	•	Risk level badge with explanation
+	•	Milestones list — each row showing sequence, title, owner, due date, dependencies
+	•	Per-milestone edit (change owner, due date, description) or delete
+	•	Add milestone button
+	•	Reorder milestones via drag
+	•	Agent observations section — risks and coordination notes the agent flagged
