+5. Risk Detection & Project-Level Chase
+5.1 Daily project review
+Once a day (part of the morning brief job), the agent runs a project review pass over every active project. For each project:
+	•	Compute progress: completed milestones / total milestones
+	•	Compute pace: progress vs. expected progress at this date
+	•	Identify overdue milestones (past due_at, not complete)
+	•	Identify blocked milestones (depending on slipping milestones)
+	•	Compute current risk_level — auto-elevate if pace is significantly off
+	•	Generate observations for the project's agent observations panel
+5.2 Risk level auto-adjustment
+Risk_level can elevate (or lower) based on observed signals:
+From
+To
+Trigger
+normal
+elevated
+Any milestone overdue OR project pace > 20% behind plan
+elevated
+critical
+Two+ milestones overdue OR escalation raised on a milestone owner OR target_completion will likely miss by >20%
+any
+low
+Project on or ahead of pace AND no recent issues — only auto-lowers from normal, never from elevated/critical (humans recover those)
+5.3 Project-level escalation
+When risk elevates from normal → elevated, the agent surfaces it to Selmen via:
+	•	Today tab Awaiting section: "⚠ Fareharbor Migration moved to elevated risk"
+	•	Daily brief: project flagged with reasoning
+	•	PWA notification (not SMS unless critical)
+When risk elevates to critical:
+	•	SMS to Selmen with summary and recommended action
+	•	Top of Today tab
+	•	Daily brief headline
+5.4 Recommended actions for risky projects
+The agent doesn't just flag risk — it suggests next steps. Common patterns:
+	•	Owner is overloaded (too many other open tasks): suggest reassignment of one milestone
+	•	Multiple milestones blocked on same upstream: suggest unblocking that upstream as priority 1
+	•	External party silent (broker, lawyer, partner): suggest Selmen places a phone call
+	•	Scope expanded mid-project: suggest re-planning to add new milestones explicitly
+
+6. Manual Project Operations
+Even with autonomous detection and risk monitoring, Selmen retains full control.
+6.1 Create a project manually
+From the Projects tab, "+ New Project" opens an empty form. Selmen can either:
+	•	Fill it out manually (name, description, target, lead)
+	•	Brain-dump into a description field and tap "Plan it for me" — same Claude-Opus planning flow as auto-detection
+6.2 Promote a task to a project
+From any task in the Today tab, a menu option "Promote to project" opens the planning flow with the task's content as the brain-dump.
+6.3 Add a milestone to an existing project
+	•	From project detail view, "+ Add milestone" opens an inline form
+	•	Set title, description, owner, due date, dependencies on existing milestones
+	•	On save, becomes a task linked to the project
+6.4 Reorder or re-sequence milestones
+	•	Drag-to-reorder in milestone list
+	•	Edit dependencies on a per-milestone basis
+	•	Saving recomputes the dispatch graph
+6.5 Pause a project
+	•	Sets status='paused'
+	•	Pending milestones not yet dispatched stay un-dispatched
+	•	Active milestones (already dispatched) continue normally
+	•	Selmen can resume any time
+6.6 Cancel a project
+	•	Sets status='cancelled'
+	•	Soft-cancels all not-yet-complete milestones (they remain in DB but are excluded from views)
+	•	Active dispatched messages are not retracted (already sent — can't unsend)
+	•	Selmen can choose to send a 'project cancelled' note to all owners (recommended)
+6.7 Mark project complete
+	•	Sets status='complete'
+	•	All non-complete milestones are auto-cancelled
+	•	Project archives but stays viewable for reference
+
+7. Tech Decisions for This Phase
+Claude usage
+	•	Project planning: claude-opus-4-7 — this is the most reasoning-heavy task in the system. Full project plans require careful sequencing and risk identification. Worth the cost.
+	•	Project detection during capture: claude-sonnet-4-6 — quick classification, doesn't need deep reasoning
+	•	Daily project review: claude-sonnet-4-6 per project; aggregate observations summarized by Opus once a week (Phase 6 pattern)
+	•	Volume estimate: Project planning costs ~$1-2 per project. With 3-5 active projects/month, that's $5-10/month total. Daily reviews add ~$5/month.
+Dependency graph
+depends_on is a JSONB array of task IDs (defined in Document 02 schema). For complex dependency graphs, this is sufficient — Postgres can query containment with @> and JSON operators.
+If projects ever exceed 50 milestones with deep nested dependencies (unlikely for Selmen's use case), consider migrating to a dedicated graph schema. For now, JSONB is fine.
+Storing milestones snapshot
+The projects table has a milestones JSONB column for a lightweight snapshot. This is for fast UI rendering — the project card can show progress without joining tasks. The snapshot is updated whenever any associated task transitions state. Keeps the Projects tab snappy.
+
