+13. Risks & Mitigations
+Risk: Project detection is too aggressive — every brain-dump becomes a project
+Mitigation: Heuristics are conservative. If false-positive rate is high in early use, tighten the prompt. The default of 'when ambiguous, treat as task' protects against noise.
+Risk: Project planning suggests bad milestones (wrong owner, unrealistic dates)
+Mitigation: Selmen reviews and edits before approval. Override patterns feed Phase 6 learning. Over time, the agent learns Selmen's planning preferences (which team members tend to own which work, typical milestone durations for project types).
+Risk: Dependency graph gets out of sync after manual edits
+Mitigation: Single source of truth is the depends_on JSONB array on each task. UI edits go through PATCH endpoints that validate (no circular refs). Background job has a daily integrity check that flags any inconsistencies.
+Risk: Risk_level oscillates as milestones complete and slip
+Mitigation: Hysteresis. Risk only auto-lowers from 'normal' (never from elevated/critical without human action). Once elevated, requires Selmen marking observation as resolved or completing milestones to drop it. This prevents flickering.
+Risk: Long-running project becomes a graveyard of stale milestones
+Mitigation: Daily review surfaces projects with no activity in 14+ days. Selmen prompted: 'This project hasn't moved. Is it still active or should we archive?' Inactivity is a leading indicator of abandonment.
+Risk: Project planning takes too long for Selmen's patience
+Mitigation: Opus planning takes 10-30 seconds. PWA shows a progress indicator with cycling status messages. If Selmen is in a hurry, he can skip planning and create the project manually with milestones added later.
+
+14. The Fareharbor Test, Round Two
+Phase 4 had a Fareharbor test focused on chase. Phase 5 has its own test focused on project-level prevention.
+During staging acceptance, run this:
+	•	Brain-dump: "We need to migrate from current booking system to FareHarbor by end of month. Nick handles tracking pixel updates. Orlando handles updating signage and operations training. Tahir handles building the reporting integration. Brandon needs to review the contract first."
+	•	Verify the agent detects this as a project and proposes structure with: Brandon's review as M1, Nick's tracking as M2 (depends on M1), Orlando + Tahir as M3 and M4 (depend on M1), final cutover as M5 (depends on all)
+	•	Approve the project
+	•	Have shadow team progress through M1 (Brandon) and M2 (Nick) normally
+	•	Have Test-Tahir's M3 stall — no response to nudges, deadline approaching
+	•	Verify: by day 3 of stall, project risk has elevated, downstream M5 shows blocked-upstream, daily brief headlines the issue, recommended action is 'phone call to Tahir + consider parallel start on M5 cutover prep'
+If this passes, the project-level Fareharbor protection is working. Multi-step initiatives are now systematically de-risked.
