+13. Risks & Mitigations
+Risk: Weekly insights are noisy or low-quality
+Mitigation: Confidence threshold default 0.8 — only surface what the model is sure about. Low-confidence insights stored for review but not pushed. If the first few weekly runs produce noise, the prompt is iterated by Selmen until quality is high.
+Risk: Approved SOP backfires (degrades quality)
+Mitigation: SOPs are versioned and reversible. Selmen can retire or edit any SOP. The agent monitors override rate per-SOP — if applying an SOP correlates with elevated override rate, that's flagged in the next weekly run as a regression.
+Risk: Selmen approves insights without reading them carefully
+Mitigation: Insight cards show evidence inline, not buried. Approve button isn't pre-selected — requires deliberate tap. Approved insights are auditable in agent_actions_log so any bad approval can be traced and reverted.
+Risk: Privacy / sensitivity of monthly team temperature read
+Mitigation: Team temperature reads are private to Selmen — never included in shareable briefs or exports. The data is observational (response times, task counts) not interpretive. The agent does not generate "performance reviews" — just patterns Selmen can act on humanly.
+Risk: Cost runs hot (weekly + monthly Opus is expensive)
+Mitigation: Total Phase 6 cost projection is $25/month — not concerning. If it grows (busier weeks, more data), set a cost ceiling and degrade to Sonnet for weekly runs if needed. Monthly run is high-value enough to justify Opus.
+Risk: Pattern detection over-fits to short-term noise
+Mitigation: 7-day windows are short. Some "patterns" will be coincidence. The 0.8 confidence threshold helps, but Selmen's approve/dismiss/snooze actions also feed back — if Selmen consistently dismisses a class of insight, the agent should learn to surface them less.
