+2. GitHub Integration
+2.1 Connection setup
+Phase 7 connects to GitHub via a Personal Access Token (PAT) with read-only scopes. Selmen generates the PAT once during setup.
+Required scopes (read-only)
+repo:status         // Read commit status
+public_repo         // Public repos (if any)
+read:org            // Org membership
+read:user           // User profile
+
+// For private repos, the full 'repo' scope is needed but stays read-only
+// because the agent never calls write endpoints.
+Why PAT instead of GitHub App
+GitHub App is more sophisticated (per-repo permissions, fine-grained scopes) but requires more setup. PAT is simpler, sufficient for read-only Phase 7 needs. If write access is added later, migrate to GitHub App at that time.
+2.2 Repository allowlist
+In Settings → GitHub Access, Selmen lists which repositories the agent has access to. Default: all repos in the takeovers org. Selmen can include or exclude specific repos.
+Recommended allowlist
+	•	takeovers-cos (this project itself — agent reads its own architecture)
+	•	takeovers-site (Vercel website code)
+	•	takeovers-platform (the unified platform per the architecture doc)
+	•	Any other tenant-specific repos
+2.3 What the agent does with GitHub access
+Use case 1: Grounding tech task dispatches
+When Selmen brain-dumps a tech task referencing code ("have Nick fix the FareHarbor webhook"), the agent:
+	•	Searches the relevant repo for files matching the keyword
+	•	Pulls the most-likely file content (e.g. apps/api/src/routes/webhooks.ts)
+	•	Includes a snippet in the dispatch brief to Nick: "Context: the current handler is at [path], here's the relevant code..."
+	•	Adds a link to the file in the brief
+Use case 2: Answering codebase questions
+Selmen asks "what's the current FareHarbor webhook handler doing?" The agent:
+	•	Identifies the relevant file via search
+	•	Reads it
+	•	Summarizes in plain English
+	•	Provides the file link
+Use case 3: Self-grounding
+The agent has access to the takeovers-cos repo, including the /docs folder containing all 13 of these documents. When Selmen asks "how does the chase logic work?" the agent reads the Phase 4 doc directly and answers grounded in its own architecture.
+Use case 4: PR/Issue context (read-only)
+Agent can list open PRs, open issues, recent commits. Surfaces these in tech-related dispatches: "Nick — there are 3 open PRs in takeovers-site that haven't been reviewed in 4+ days."
+2.4 GitHub API operations
+// Operations the agent can perform (read-only)
+GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}
+GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/contents/{path}     // Read file
+GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/git/trees/{tree_sha}?recursive=1  // Tree listing
+GET /search/code?q=...                         // Code search across allowlist
+GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/commits              // Recent commits
+GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls                // Open PRs
+GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues               // Open issues
+
+// Operations the agent does NOT perform in Phase 7:
+// PUT /repos/{owner}/{repo}/contents/{path}   // Write file — explicitly disabled
+// POST /repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues           // Open issue — disabled
+// POST /repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls            // Open PR — disabled
+// POST /repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues/comments  // Comment — disabled
+2.5 Caching strategy
+GitHub API has rate limits (5K requests/hour authenticated). Cache aggressively:
+	•	Repository tree structure cached for 1 hour
+	•	File contents cached for 30 minutes
+	•	Search results cached for 15 minutes
+	•	Cache key includes commit SHA so updates invalidate correctly
+	•	Cache stored in Redis (already in stack)
