+
+8. Testing Plan
+8.1 Unit tests
+	•	Drive search query construction
+	•	File content generation prompt rendering
+	•	GitHub PAT scope validation
+	•	Code search result ranking
+	•	Cache key generation and invalidation
+8.2 Integration tests
+	•	End-to-end create file: capture → Claude generation → Drive create → confirmation
+	•	End-to-end search file: capture → Drive search → result selection → context use
+	•	End-to-end edit file: capture → draft → approval → Drive update
+	•	End-to-end code grounding: tech task → repo search → file read → dispatch with context
+	•	OAuth scope expansion: existing Gmail OAuth + new Drive scope
+8.3 Security tests
+	•	Verify drive.file scope cannot access unauthorized files
+	•	Verify PAT cannot perform write operations even if API endpoint constructed manually
+	•	Verify deleted folders are removed from authorization
+	•	Verify cache doesn't leak content between users (single-user system, but defense-in-depth)
+8.4 Adversarial tests
+	•	Brain-dump containing file path that doesn't exist — verify graceful failure
+	•	Search query with special characters — verify safe handling
+	•	File content with prompt injection text — verify Claude's classification stays bounded
+	•	PAT revoked outside the system — verify next call detects and prompts re-auth
+
+9. Dependencies & Prerequisites
+Before starting Phase 7
+	•	Phases 1-6 complete and stable in production
+	•	Google Cloud project from Phase 3 still active
+	•	Selmen has decided which Drive folders to authorize (operations, marketing, templates, reports — recommended starting set)
+	•	GitHub PAT generated with read-only scopes
+	•	Repository allowlist decided (recommended: takeovers-cos, takeovers-site, takeovers-platform)
+
+10. Risks & Mitigations
+Risk: Agent reads or exfiltrates sensitive files
+Mitigation: drive.file scope strictly limits to authorized folders. Selmen authorizes folders explicitly via Drive picker. Sensitive folders (financial, legal, personal) are simply never authorized. If sensitive content lands in an authorized folder by mistake, Selmen revokes the folder.
+Risk: Generated file content is wrong or off-tone
+Mitigation: Generated files are a starting draft. Selmen reviews before sharing. The agent learns Selmen's style over time per Phase 6 — first month of generated docs may need editing, less so over time.
+Risk: GitHub PAT is leaked
+Mitigation: PAT is read-only — leakage doesn't enable write damage. Stored encrypted at rest. Easy to rotate. If leaked, Selmen revokes in GitHub settings, generates new one, updates env var.
+Risk: Code summarization is technically wrong
+Mitigation: Code summaries are framed as "here's what I think this does — verify with Nick". Never presented as authoritative. Critical for the agent to acknowledge uncertainty when summarizing complex code.
+Risk: Drive API rate limits during heavy use
+Mitigation: Drive API quotas are generous (10K queries/100sec/user). The agent's volume is well under. Implement exponential backoff just in case.
+Risk: Selmen authorizes a folder, then later wants to revoke
+Mitigation: Settings page has revoke per folder. On revoke, agent immediately stops accessing. Cache for that folder is purged. file_references rows referencing the folder remain (for audit) but new operations rejected.
+
+11. Phase 7 Sign-Off Checklist
+	•	All acceptance criteria in Section 7 verified in staging
+	•	All Section 8 tests passed including security and adversarial tests
+	•	Drive folder authorization flow works end-to-end
+	•	GitHub PAT setup and validation works
+	•	At least 5 real Drive operations executed in staging (create, search, read, edit-draft, attach-to-email)
+	•	At least 5 real GitHub reads executed in staging (file read, search, tree, PRs, commits)
+	•	Self-grounding test passes — agent answers a question about its own architecture by reading /docs
+	•	All file/repo authorization data migrated to production
+	•	Documentation in /docs is up to date
+With Phase 7 complete, the agent has reach into both Drive (cloud files) and GitHub (codebase context). Combined with all prior phases, the system can run virtually any operational task Selmen would otherwise handle himself — capturing the thought, finding or creating the needed artifacts, dispatching to the team in their style, chasing follow-up, escalating when needed, planning multi-step initiatives, and learning from every interaction.
+This concludes the seven build phases. The remaining three documents are visual diagrams that round out the documentation set: System Architecture Diagram, Data Flow Diagram, and Agent Decision Tree + Deployment Diagram. Drop them in /docs alongside everything else.
